The `console.log` function in JavaScript is used to output the value of a variable or expression to the console (the default console for most browsers). When you use `console.log`, it will display the value of the variable on the screen.

Here's an example:

```javascript
let name = "John";
console.log(name); // Output: John

// You can also log multiple values at once:
console.log("Name", "Age", "City");
```

In this example, `name` is logged twice because we're using two commas as separators between the different values.

If you want to log the value of a variable without displaying it, you can use the `console.warn()` method instead:

```javascript
let message = "Hello, world!";
console.warn(message);
```

This will only show a warning message if the variable has been assigned a value and is not null or undefined. If the variable is already set to a value that can be printed, it won't cause any warnings.

